    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="primary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP" source="https://www.zotero.org/groups/382445/items/8ENX9UZ5">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name><w><unclear>Ἀ</unclear>ρι<unclear>στο</unclear>μένε<unclear>ος</unclear></w></name></persName> <w><unclear>ε</unclear>ἱμὶ</w> <w>σᾶμα</w>
                 </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp><app><note>Text of Sansone in Cannata et al.</note></app></listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>I am the memorial of Aristomenes</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>A remarkable monumental rock-cut tomb deep in the hinterland of Akrai/Netum (suggested to fall within the territory of ancient Akrai), with a Greek name and archaic letter forms compatible with the Syracusan alphabet. Nothing remains within the tomb, whcih was presumably robbed out in antiquity (although Catagnino Berlinghieri et al. 2026 speculate on the (unlikely) possibility of the monument as cenotaph on that basis). The hypogeum shows signs of prehistoric presence/use also, and so the site has a long history of usage. Whether the deceased was Greek or 'hellenized' indigenous is impossible to know. The 'speaking' formula is attested elsewhere on the island, such as at Selinunte or Megara Hyblaea. The text shows Doric elements.</p>
            </div>
